Reconstructing Native American Migrations from Whole-genome and Whole-exome Data (Simon Gravel - 15 November, 2013)
The 1000 Genomes Project provides a unique opportunity for improving our understanding of population genetic history by providing over a hundred sequenced low coverage genomes and exomes from Colombian (CLM), Mexican-American (MXL), and Puerto Rican (PUR) populations. Estimated Native American ancestry is 48% in MXL, 25% in CLM, and 13% in PUR. These ancestral populations likely split in close succession: the most likely scenario, based on a peopling of the Americas 16 thousand years ago (kya), supports that the MXL Ancestors split 12.2kya, with a subsequent split of the ancestors to CLM and PUR 11.7kya
